Tetracyclines, chloramphenicol, erythromycin, and clindamycin. Tetracyclines are active in vitro against most urinary tract pathogens, Chlamydia, Mycoplasma pneumoniae, Brucella, rickettsiae, and Nocardia. Chloramphenicol is used primarily for anaerobic infections, Haemophilus influenzae meningitis, and infections due to Salmonella typhi. Erythromycin is active in vitro against M. pneumoniae, Streptococcus pneumoniae, and group A beta-hemolytic streptococci. Erythromycin may be used as prophylactic therapy for subacute bacterial endocarditis and for recurrence of acute rheumatic fever in patients who are allergic to penicillin. Clindamycin should be used only for the treatment of anaerobic infections. Tetracycline may cause gastrointestinal upset phototoxic dermatitis